{"key":"processedPost-9517835","value":{"id":9517835,"first":9515407,"last":9521375,"when":1230665314,"utime":"12/30/08 09:28 PM","content":"If you're going to build a flowhood, check out <a href=\"http://www.fungifun.org/English/Flowhood\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">Anno's site</a> first.&nbsp; <br /><br />I have used the series 1 from FP for many years on the same filter.&nbsp; Simply duct tape a furnace filter over the air intake and your expensive hepa will last nearly forever.<br /><br />Laminar flow is straight line airflow.&nbsp; It means when the sterile air hits your hands and tools, it will flow along and around them without creating eddys or other turbulent currents.&nbsp; The 'lighter test' is done by holding the lighter at all places within the flow area.&nbsp; You should see the flame bend but not go out, and it should bend straight over, not flickering from side to side.&nbsp; The intensity of the flow should be the same, and the flame should not bend more at one part of the work area than another.&nbsp; Laminar flow is achieved by creating pressure in a plenum behind the filter.&nbsp; By having an even pressure <i>behind</i> the filter, the flow through and out the other side is the same everywhere.<br />RR","title":"Re: to buy or to build"}}